value: <sup xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">&  sung</sup> and knows the old story of
<s xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">the Nut brown maid.</s>

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          Anon is sometimes woman; sometimes man; he is the

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          common voice;
<sup xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">He hears <s>of</s> them [illeg.]</sup> Anon goes round the country singing.
<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
<sup xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">[</sup>He has a very quick eye, connected, for the eye is the

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          youthful sense, rather with the body than the mind.
<sup xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">]</sup>

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          Anon
<sup xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"><s>He</s></sup>has no house. He lives a roaming out of door

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          country life, going from village to village,

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          stopping 
            at (a) the back door
<sup xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">,</sup>oftener than at the front,

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          going 
            along (alojg) grassy paths over the hills.
<sup xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">|</sup> By choosing a view

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          carefully to shut out a chimney or a
            bungalow (bungalwo), we can still

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          see,

<s xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">in 
            some (osome), or up on some down,</s> what Anon saw.

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          the bird 
            haunted (ha unted) 
            reed (red) whispering fen; the down covered

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          with turf; and the scar, long healed, over the
<s xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">down</s>
<sup xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">hill</sup>

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          along which Anon came when he made his journeys.

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          He was garrulous; 
            loose (looe) lipped; taking from other peoples

<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
          mouths here a story, there a stanza. But now and again he
<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>

<s xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">as we 
            call (acll) it</s>, an artist;
<s xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">the words are complete; the song</s>
<br xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0"/>
<s xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0">finished.</s>
